snippet.title: OnePlus One hands-on
snippet.description: Powered by CyanogenMod, this quad-core Android smartphone will be available for just $299 around the world in 16 countries, including the US and UK.

snippet.title: Apps to track the flu
snippet.description: It's that time of year when you'll go to any length to avoid germs. Keep the flu and other seasonal illnesses at bay by consulting your smartphone first for any local outbreaks. In this Tech Minute, CNET's Kara Tsuboi reports on apps and sites that track the flu.

snippet.title: Twitter CEO heads to China to meet with officials
snippet.description: Twitter has been banned from China since 2009, but could be an extremely lucrative market for the service if the ban could be lifted.

snippet.title: Flu predictions get more accurate
snippet.description: Google's annual Flu Trends metric was wildly off last year. But scientists were able to leverage the company's data to design a far more successful system.

snippet.title: Flappy48 combines Flappy Bird and 2048 into a single clone
snippet.description: The title requires users to glide through gaps in blocks while collecting squares that will add up to higher scores.

snippet.title: Play Flappy Bird clone Tiny Bird on your Pebble smartwatch
snippet.description: Miss Flappy Bird? Tiny Bird is a clone of the addictive game that wants to cheer you up.

snippet.title: The search for an awesome Flappy Bird replacement
snippet.description: Now that Flappy Bird has been pulled from the app stores, I've put together a collection of knockoffs that get some things right, but mostly miss the mark.

snippet.title: Flappy Bird to be grounded by its creator?
snippet.description: Dong Nguyen, creator of the app that's been making $50,000 a day in ad revenue (and that some have called the worst smartphone game ever), tweets that he's pulling the game.

snippet.title: Forget Flappy Bird. We're all hooked on 2048
snippet.description: The latest addictive game already has popular parody versions, Gmail beefs up its security, and Samsung has a new TV that costs as much as a house.
